<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">FBA0007/12-13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Andrew Jackson—Written evidence</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am a Chartered Tax Advisor, in practice as Head of Tax at a medium-sized accountancy firm.  I am also a member of the Tax Panel of the UK200 Group, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">an association of independent accountancy and legal firms dealing largely with the SME market.  I am however writing in a personal capa</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">city</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to provide evidence concerning the likely impact of the draft legislation on the reallocation of “excess profits” of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> mixed partnerships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Assumption of profitability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A primary concern is that the legislation is predicated on the assumption that partnerships are consistently profitable.  The simple mechanical rules for the calculation and reallocation of excess profits </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">do not recognise the existence of losses.  Consequently, where a partnership alternates between profit and loss there appears to be no way for the profits and losses to be matched: where profits are reallocated to an individual in one year, losses </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">arising</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the next will remain in the company</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, and could not be carried back against the individual’s taxable profits</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This will necessarily result</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, year on year,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> in the taxable profits exceeding the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">total </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">eco</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">nomic profits made</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> if the partnership makes losses.  It</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> also removes the possibility of obtaining relief for losses made in the past which are being carried forward for use against future profits</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Particularly in the current economic climate, it appears unreasonable to assume that any business will be consist</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ently profitable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">No mechanism is included whereby </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which might</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> alleviate this issue.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  Possible mechanisms c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ould include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Permitting the reallocation of losses where related profits have been reallocated</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Reallocating the whole of the partnership interest </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">for tax purposes, so the individual is deemed to hold it directly and to be entitled to all profits, losses and gains</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Enabling the removal of the corporate partners from the structure without an immediate tax charge (some form of holdover relief may be app</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ropriate)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Including a “tax avoidance motive” test </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to exclude cases where there is a bona fide commercial reason for the inclusion of the company</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Grandfathering existing </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to exclude them from the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">legislation (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">perhaps </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">where a bona fide </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">commercial reason is agreed to exist</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> while including all new partnerships</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The impact can be illustrated by taking</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a mixed partnership (based on a case I am aware of) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">has substantial losses brought forward due to a large investment in plant qualifyi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ng for enhanced capital allowances.  These losses, which are expressly intended by Parliament, are being carried forward by the various corporate and individual partners to relieve the income to be derived from operating the plant.   In this case the draft</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> rules would operate to reallocate profits from certain corporate members </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to related individuals.  Those individuals would be unable to make use of the losses carried forward in the related company, and so would be entirely denied relief for their share of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the capital investment which Parliament is trying to encourage by offering enhanced capital allowances.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">One option </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">for the above partnership </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">might be to disclaim the capital allowances to the extent that they exceed profits arising (assuming that the d</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">eadline for doing so has not expired).  This has two adverse effects:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Once disclaimed, allowances can only be claimed in the future at 18% on a reducing balance basis, and so in future years may not relieve the whole of the profits – whereas if claimed in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the first year they would relieve all profits until they are exhausted.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The claim has to be made by the partnership, and so doing so to benefit one partner will disadvantage other partners regardless of whether they are caught by the mixed partnership r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ules directly.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Corporate veil</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A second concern is that the rules are somewhat arbitrary in their regard for the corporate veil.  Similar legal and commercial situations are treated very differently.  If Messrs A and B wish to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">acquire and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">carry on a busin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ess jointly:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If they form a partnership or LLP</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to acquire the business</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, the profits will be subject to income tax in their hands</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If they form a company</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to acquire the business</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, each owning 50% of the shares,  the profits will be subject to corporation tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (there is no partnership so the rules cannot apply)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If they form two companies (each of them owning 100% of the shares of one company) and the companies go into partnership</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to acquire the business</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, the profits of each company will be reallocated to the ow</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ner and subjected to income tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (s850D would deem them to be partners)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If they form two companies (each of them owning 50% of the shares of each company) and the companies go into partnership</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to acquire the business</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, 50% of the profits of each company will</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> be reallocated to each of the owners and subjected to income tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (s850D again)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If they form a partnership which forms a company to acquire the business, the profits will be subject to corporation tax (as the partnership is not mixed there can be no </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">reallocation)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In each case but the first there is a corporate veil between the individuals and the business, but in some cases it is bypassed and in others it is not</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A further anomaly could exist where Messrs A and B had each been operating their own </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">trading company separately, but then these companies go into partnership.  The rules as drafted are not clear as to whether this would be deemed to be a mixed partnership (as the individuals could have chosen to go into partnership themselves and so s850D </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">could apply), and if so how much of the profit should be subject to reallocation.  If the two businesses are similar this could be a complex issue to disentangle.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In the light of the fact</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Normal commercial partnerships are exposed to l</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">osses, and may already have incurred them, but the proposals would deny relief for them in many cases;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Where profits are made, in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the majority of cases the presence of a company in a partnership would only defer </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">taxation </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(and that only partly), rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> leading to the overall tax l</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">iability being significantly reduced; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">HMRC have expressed no concerns about tax avoidance where a sole trader chooses to incorporate (and have in fact indicated (in connection with the GAAR) that it is “obvious” that to do </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">so is not abusive)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> targeted anti-avoidance rule (such as the one proposed for loss reallocations) may be more effective and inflict less collateral damage</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">t is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">concerning </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">these changes would introduce </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">significant anomalies</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> into business tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, but no policy reason has been articulated to explain why partnerships should be treated harshly compared to other business structures.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I have not yet had sufficient time to digest the report by the Office of Tax Simplification into the taxation o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">f partnerships, but from an initial review it would appear that some of the possibilities they mention (such as taxing partnerships directly) could render the profit reallocation rules redundant.  To make far-reaching changes to partnership taxation before</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that report has been considered and acted upon would seem to be acting unduly quickly.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>